    Natasha Gillies3 years ago on Google
    5/5
    I came here seeking a break from tagines, and was rewarded by a diverse and more innovative menu than is typical in Marrakech, offering really good, fresh food at a reasonable price. The terrace offers beautiful views over the city, but it …
    I came here seeking a break from tagines, and was rewarded by a diverse and more innovative menu than is typical in Marrakech, offering really good, fresh food at a reasonable price. The terrace offers beautiful views over the city, but it felt a little chilly on the night I visited so I opted to eat inside (they did offer me blankets, though). The interior is chic and modern, and the staff are friendly and attentive. The music is perhaps a little loud but it didn't bother me, though I was eating solo. My meal (a chicken and avocado wrap) was delicious and exactly what I was after. I also had a glass of their orange juice which was freshly squeeze and a generous portion. Following the meal I was given a pot of mint tea and a small plate of tiny meringues which were delicious. A true gem.

    Medina

    Hammam bath houses and covered spice and textile souks line the maze of cobblestoned lanes in the Medina, which occupies Marrakesh’s original fortified citadel. At night, Jemaa el-Fna square teems with snake charmers, folk dancers, and street food vendors serving all manner of food. Bahia Palace and Le Jardin Secret are 19th-century complexes open to the public, with ornate courtyards, mosaics, and gardens.
